const title = "Feng et al. (2026) - H I 21-cm Properties of IRAS 04296+2923 - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">H I 21-cm Line Properties of the Nearby LIRG IRAS 04296+2923</h1>
        
        <div class="paper-meta">
            <p><strong>Authors:</strong> Guixiang Feng, Zhongzu Wu, Chuanpeng Zhang, Ming Zhu</p>
            <p><strong>arXiv ID:</strong> <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11899" target="_blank">2603.11899</a></p>
            <p><strong>Date:</strong> 2026-03-12</p>
            <p><strong>Status:</strong> Accepted by A&amp;A</p>
        </div>

        <div class="abstract-box">
            <h3>Abstract</h3>
            <p>Archival VLA and FAST H I 21-cm imaging plus multi-band radio continuum reveal that IRAS 04296+2923 resides in a small group of five H I-detected galaxies and that its nearest companion HI 0432+2926 has comparable H I mass and a small velocity offset; both show rotation-dominated H I kinematics while radio continuum is concentrated in IRAS 04296+2923's nucleus, indicative of a compact, young, dust-obscured starburst<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="section-0">Key Findings</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>H I imaging identifies five group members and a close companion (HI 0432+2926) at projected ~40 kpc with Δv ≈ 26 km s<sup>-1</sup><sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
            <li>Both IRAS 04296+2923 and its companion display regular H I velocity fields and double-horn profiles consistent with rotation-dominated kinematics<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
            <li>Radio continuum is detected only from IRAS 04296+2923 and is nuclear and compact; spectral modeling shows a strong free–free component at &gt;30 GHz and a high FIR-to-radio ratio (q_8.4 ≈ 3.2), indicating a young, dust-obscured nuclear starburst<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
            <li>The authors favour a scenario where the LIRG activity is driven by internal processes (e.g., bar-induced inflow) possibly modulated by weak tidal interactions in the small group, rather than an advanced merger<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>.</li>
        </ul>

